Please help our dear friend and surfing legend Coco Nogales!

During the historic swell at Isla Todos Santos on January 13th, Coco broke his pelvis and sacrum after getting caught inside by a cleanup set. He was taken to the hospital in Ensenada where he stayed for almost two days before being told they would not operate on him and was asked to leave the hospital. After further consultation with multiple medical specialists, the decision was made to transport him to the U.S.A. where he could receive immediate emergency surgery for his life-threatening injuries.

Coco’s surgery was a success, and he is in good spirits as he embarks on the lengthy rehabilitation process. Unfortunately given the circumstances, he was unable to receive any medical insurance assistance and now faces an overwhelming financial bill and needs our help!

With love, respect and gratitude we thank you for any financial contributions, and for sharing this request for help during Coco’s time of need with others. 

Link in bio to donate and share. 
—————————————————
¡Ayuda a nuestro querida amiga y leyenda del surf Coco Nogales!

Durante el oleaje histórico en Isla Todos Santos el 13 de enero, Coco se rompió la pelvis y el sacro después de quedar atrapado adentro de varias olas grandes. Inmediatamente lo llevaron al hospital de Ensenada, donde permaneció  casi dos días antes de que le dijeran que no lo operarían y le pidieron que abandonara el hospital. Después de más consultas con múltiples especialistas médicos, se tomó la decisión de transportarlo a los Estados Unidos, donde podría recibir una cirugía de emergencia inmediata por sus lesiones potencialmente mortales.

La cirugía de Coco fue un éxito y está de buen humor mientras se embarca en el largo proceso de rehabilitación. Desafortunadamente, dadas las circunstancias, no pudo recibir ninguna asistencia de seguro médico y ahora enfrenta una factura financiera abrumadora y necesita nuestra ayuda.

Con amor, respeto y gratitud, le agradecemos cualquier contribución financiera y compartir esta solicitud de ayuda durante el tiempo de necesidad de Coco con otros.

Link in bio para donar y compartir.

Please help Tom Lowe...During the recent monumental swell at Teahupoo, Tahiti, Tom endured a bad wipeout. His resulting injuries from hitting the reef required he be airlifted to the hospital where he underwent multiple emergency surgeries. He is currently in stable condition but will need to remain under close watch in the hospital for the coming days.

Unfortunately, Tom’s travel insurance will not cover his medical treatment, so we are seeking the kindness and generosity of Tom’s global surf family, friends and compassion of the community, to help assist with his ongoing medical expenses.

Anyone who has ever met Tom knows him as a humble, kind and talented surfer who is a dedicated family man to his wife Tess, daughter Tigerlilly and soon-to-be baby-on-the-way. Tom has a long road ahead, but true to his nature, he is positive, in a fighting spirit. 
Tom and his family extend their heartfelt gratitude for all the love and support during their time of need. 

Link in bio to donate and share.

Playa Zicatela, Puerto Escondido.  Everyday is a challenge, especially when it gets big.  Sessions here are always rife with lessons in timing, wave judgement, positioning, patience and humility and always leave the desire for the chance to try again.  Despite what looks and feels like a daunting and impossibly long wall down the line, “20 feet deeper than you think” was the lesson for the day.  Notes taken… 

Video: @paco_calleja

May Daze.  The swells are beginning to blur together but the rides are always etched into memory with distinguished detail. 🇲🇽 🙌🏽✨

Video: @hunter_weiss  @nnm.project

Poetry in motion at Playa Zicatela, Puerto Escondido.

I was in deep water slowly inching my way in toward the lineup as the the first shades of grey light appeared above the mountains to the east.  Through the dark I could make out the unmistakable shapes of a big set refracting through the deep water canyon offshore.  But It was still too early to surf safely given the size of the swell (Surfline high-def cams see incredibly well in the dark and I also lightened the video in post for our viewing enjoyment). I sat upright on my board and admired from backstage the five wave set unload on the shallow sandbank inside with flawless succession. 

Ten minutes later, we would enter the lineup and navigate our first rides in the twilight.  Amazing waves were ridden by many throughout the day, but there was not another set of the size and perfection of these pre-dawn unicorns. 

The mystery of never quite knowing exactly when gems like these may show up is part of the  allure of the game.  But we do know where, and that is what keeps so many of us coming back to this magical beach swell after swell, year after year. 

🇲🇽 🙏🏽🌊✨

I had lost feeling in my feet, and the thin arctic air set my lungs ablaze with each labored inhale .  But I had to keep moving as it was the only way to stay warm, and I needed to keep pace with my expedition partners as I had assured them before the trip that I could, and I would.  One foot at a time, I kept cadence, following the tracks in the snow set before me by professional big mountain snowboarder, @taylorgodber and world renowned mountaineer and ice scientist @alisoncriscitiello 

My entire life had been devoted to the ocean following my passion of surfing.  I could count on my near frost bitten fingers the number of times in my life I had voluntarily taken an extended trip that didn’t in some way involve the ocean.  Now, here I was, ascending a glacier in interior British Columbia, a metaphoric fish out of water.  But knowing the intrinsic connection between the mountains and ocean, I had jumped at the opportunity to join this adventure supported by @parley.tv and @talisker with one of the world’s leading glaciologists.

“The ice on our earth holds some of the longest records of our climate history.  Changes In climate that get recorded in the ice tell a story that we can’t see without own eyes.” Shared Dr. Cristiello. 

There is a profound depth of wisdom found within the ice and those who study it that can both help us better understand the landscape of the current climate crisis, and guide us on a path towards re-instating the
harmonious balance we are meant to be living with the natural world. 

Find the full short film “The Stories the Ice Holds” at the link in the bio and stay tuned for another amazing collaborative project between @parley.tv and @talisker . 

@alisoncriscitiello

Introducing the extraordinary, Talisker 45-Year Glacial Edge Whiskey Inspired by the partnership with @parley.tv to help protect and preserve our planets most precious ecosystems. 

I’m grateful to have played a part of the final stages of this 45 year project which consisted of some wild adventures in the Arctic Highlands and in-depth look at what is happening in our mountain and glacial ecosystems. There is a profound depth of wisdom found within the ice that can both help us better understand the landscape of the current climate crisis, and guide us on a path towards re-instating the harmonious balance we are meant to be living with the natural world. 

Find the full short film from this collaborative project “The Stories the Ice Holds” at the link in the bio. 

And for the Whiskey lovers out there, keep an eye out for those beautiful Talisker-Parley bottles…each purchase gives back to help protect our planet.
